  16 class _State:
  17     def __init__(
  18         self, source, save_marker=False, restore=False
  19     ):  # type: (_Source, Optional[bool], Optional[bool]) -> None
  20         self._source = source
  21         self._save_marker = save_marker
  22         self.restore = restore
  23 
  24     def __enter__(self):  # type: () -> None
  25         # Entering this context manager - save the state
  26         if PY2:
  27             # Python 2.7 does not allow to directly copy
  28             # an iterator, so we have to make tees of the original
  29             # chars iterator.
  30             self._source._chars, self._chars = itertools.tee(self._source._chars)
  31         else:
  32             self._chars = copy(self._source._chars)
  33         self._idx = self._source._idx
  34         self._current = self._source._current
  35         self._marker = self._source._marker
  36 
  37         return self
  38 
  39     def __exit__(self, exception_type, exception_val, trace):
  40         # Exiting this context manager - restore the prior state
  41         if self.restore or exception_type:
  42             self._source._chars = self._chars
  43             self._source._idx = self._idx
  44             self._source._current = self._current
  45             if self._save_marker:
  46                 self._source._marker = self._marker
  47

  49 class _StateHandler:
  50     """
  51     State preserver for the Parser.
  52     """
  53 
  54     def __init__(self, source):  # type: (Source) -> None
  55         self._source = source
  56         self._states = []
  57 
  58     def __call__(self, *args, **kwargs):
  59         return _State(self._source, *args, **kwargs)
  60 
  61     def __enter__(self):  # type: () -> None
  62         state = self()
  63         self._states.append(state)
  64         return state.__enter__()
  65 
  66     def __exit__(self, exception_type, exception_val, trace):
  67         state = self._states.pop()
  68         return state.__exit__(exception_type, exception_val, trace)

  71 class Source(unicode):
  72     EOF = TOMLChar("\0")
  73 
  74     def __init__(self, _):  # type: (unicode) -> None
  75         super(Source, self).__init__()
  76 
  77         # Collection of TOMLChars
  78         self._chars = iter([(i, TOMLChar(c)) for i, c in enumerate(self)])
  79 
  80         self._idx = 0
  81         self._marker = 0
  82         self._current = TOMLChar("")
  83 
  84         self._state = _StateHandler(self)
  85 
  86         self.inc()
  87 
  88     def reset(self):
  89         # initialize both idx and current
  90         self.inc()
  91 
  92         # reset marker
  93         self.mark()
  94 
  95     @property
  96     def state(self):  # type: () -> _StateHandler
  97         return self._state
  98 
  99     @property
 100     def idx(self):  # type: () -> int
 101         return self._idx
 102 
 103     @property
 104     def current(self):  # type: () -> TOMLChar
 105         return self._current
 106 
 107     @property
 108     def marker(self):  # type: () -> int
 109         return self._marker
 110 
 111     def extract(self):  # type: () -> unicode
 112         """
 113         Extracts the value between marker and index
 114         """
 115         return self[self._marker : self._idx]
 116 
 117     def inc(self, exception=None):  # type: (Optional[ParseError.__class__]) -> bool
 118         """
 119         Increments the parser if the end of the input has not been reached.
 120         Returns whether or not it was able to advance.
 121         """
 122         try:
 123             self._idx, self._current = next(self._chars)
 124 
 125             return True
 126         except StopIteration:
 127             self._idx = len(self)
 128             self._current = self.EOF
 129             if exception:
 130                 raise self.parse_error(exception)
 131 
 132             return False
 133 
 134     def inc_n(self, n, exception=None):  # type: (int, Exception) -> bool
 135         """
 136         Increments the parser by n characters
 137         if the end of the input has not been reached.
 138         """
 139         for _ in range(n):
 140             if not self.inc(exception=exception):
 141                 return False
 142 
 143         return True
 144 
 145     def consume(self, chars, min=0, max=-1):
 146         """
 147         Consume chars until min/max is satisfied is valid.
 148         """
 149         while self.current in chars and max != 0:
 150             min -= 1
 151             max -= 1
 152             if not self.inc():
 153                 break
 154 
 155         # failed to consume minimum number of characters
 156         if min > 0:
 157             self.parse_error(UnexpectedCharError)
 158 
 159     def end(self):  # type: () -> bool
 160         """
 161         Returns True if the parser has reached the end of the input.
 162         """
 163         return self._current is self.EOF
 164 
 165     def mark(self):  # type: () -> None
 166         """
 167         Sets the marker to the index's current position
 168         """
 169         self._marker = self._idx
 170 
 171     def parse_error(
 172         self, exception=ParseError, *args
 173     ):  # type: (ParseError.__class__, ...) -> ParseError
 174         """
 175         Creates a generic "parse error" at the current position.
 176         """
 177         line, col = self._to_linecol()
 178 
 179         return exception(line, col, *args)
 180 
 181     def _to_linecol(self):  # type: () -> Tuple[int, int]
 182         cur = 0
 183         for i, line in enumerate(self.splitlines()):
 184             if cur + len(line) + 1 > self.idx:
 185                 return (i + 1, self.idx - cur)
 186 
 187             cur += len(line) + 1
 188 
 189         return len(self.splitlines()), 0
